<font color="#FF0000">REFLECTIONS </font><br>
<tt>Wed Dec 18 20:37:27 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
Where does this end? When does this beast DIE? After twenty five years we contiually crawl back into the war. Junkies for the pain. If only we could have understood. If only there was some miniscule ion of credibility for what we did;<br>
What we forced the VietNamese into doing against us. I'm not concerned about Fonda or Clintons actions back then. Fonda's<br>
married and out of the picture. Clinton wants to dictate our lives. He makes me nervous now. In Nam I sat in a tower, or at a gate and practiced being a target. In a no-fire zone thats the only choice you have. I saw a lot of good people come and go, and miss quite a few more. Kube Heinlein Williams Poncho, all of them. Friends made because there was nobody else, but good friends none the less. <br>
I was a peacefull person back then, and I'm a peacefull person now. But VietNam was the only real home I know. If nothing else, it was honest. Coming back here was really no joy. The games, the lies, deceits. Unchecked giggles behind my back, the mockery from the status quo. Fuckers never went there, never put shit on the line. But through money and fast talk they took our jobs, our wives, our lives, and cast us out. Sometimes, as peacefull as I am, I miss the honesty.<br>
Erin Brooker<br>
Head and Head, 54th Signal Battallion, IFFV<br>
NhaTrang 69/70
